<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06249167 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06249167 </ACCESS><LEADPARA>  By the time Manuel Noriega's trial ends, taxpayers may have shelled out morethan $175 million -- and perhaps even more than $200 million -- to overthrow,arrest and try the former leader of Panama.;   Noriega's trial on drugtrafficking and racketeering charges began today and should last three to fourmonths.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  TAXPAYERS' TAB ON NORIEGA: $175 MILLION  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     Expenses associated with the case include $163 million to finance the 1989U.S. invasion of Panama, according to the Pentagon. Trial-related costs havebeen estimated by attorneys involved in the case at $12 million to $40million.;   Richard Gregorie, the ex-federal prosecutor who wrote theindictment, defends the expense. &quot;It is important for the world to recognizethat the United States did everything possible to see that this man got a fairtrial,&quot; he said.;   &quot;It is reprehensible overkill,&quot; said Fletcher Baldwin, lawprofessor at the University of Florida. He calls the invasion &quot;probably themost expensive execution of a search warrant ever.&quot;;   See story on trial,Page 10A.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Fort Lauderdale Sun-Sentinel  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Miami  </CITY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910905  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Thursday  </DAY><MONTH>  September  </MONTH><PG.COL>  1A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  161  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Thursday, September 5, 199100249167,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENGFRONT  </LANGUAGE></DOC>